# Note: for the next function to work, the data needs to be sorted by post ID.

def add_rater_id(df, post_id_column):
    rater_id = []
    current_post_id = -1
    for post_id in df[post_id_column]:
        if post_id != current_post_id:  # If current index has changed
            # Set rater index to 1
            rater_index = 1
            # Save the current input index
            current_post_id = post_id
        # Add the rater id to the list and increment it for the next row
        rater_id.append(rater_index)
        rater_index += 1
    return rater_id

batch_res['rater_id'] = add_rater_id(batch_res, 'Positions')

for index, row in batch_res.iterrows():
    if row['biospheric_mean'] > row['egocentric_mean']:
        label.append(2)
    elif row['biospheric_mean'] < row['egocentric_mean']:
        label.append(1)
    else:
        biospheric_dist = abs(row['help_beings'] - row['protect_environment'])
        egocentric_dist = abs(row['quality_of_life'] - row['thier_own_good'])
        if biospheric_dist < egocentric_dist:
            label.append(2) # the means are equal but biospheric tagging are more close to each other
        elif egocentric_dist < biospheric_dist:
            label.append(1) # the means are equal but egocentric tagging are more close to each other
        else:
            label.append(0) # the means are equal and the closeness of the tagging are also equal (equivalent tagging)
batch_res['label'] = label

        if ((batch_res['our_classification'].iloc[i] == 'egocentric' or batch_res['our_classification'].iloc[i] == 'mixed') and batch_res['comment_label'].iloc[i] == 1) or ((batch_res['our_classification'].iloc[i] == 'biospheric'or batch_res['our_classification'].iloc[i] == 'mixed') and batch_res['comment_label'].iloc[i] == 2):
            batch_res['correct_comment'].iloc[i] = 1
        else:
            batch_res['correct_comment'].iloc[i] = 0

from nltk.probability import FreqDist
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def present_freqDist(words_column):
    # creates list of all words from all posts
    tokenized_words = [word for post in words_column.tolist() for word in post]

    fdist = FreqDist(tokenized_words)
    print(f'Number of words: {len(tokenized_words)}')
    print(f'Number of unique words: {len(set(tokenized_words))}') # Set removes duplicates from a list

    print(f'The five most common words: {fdist.most_common(5)}')ng

Removing stopwords and punctuation¶

In [161]:
from nltk.corpus import stopwords 
# nltk.download('stopwords') # first-time use only
stop_words = stopwords.words('english')  # list of stop words from nltk library
In [162]:
def clean_text(text):
    # remove stop words and punctuation
    filtered_text=[]
    for word in text:
        if word not in stop_words and word.isalnum(): # word.isalnum - check if words are not panctuations marks (i.e., alphabets or numbers)
            filtered_text.append(word)
    return filtered_text

batch_res["post_words_clean"] = batch_res["post_words"].apply(clean_text)
